        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>22d August 5619</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I enclose you some extracts<lb/> from a couple of letters received
                from my father<lb/> some time since but which from press of engagements<lb/> and
                absence from town I have been unable to send<lb/> you until now. If you think them
                of sufficient<lb/> interest to publish in the Occident, please do so in<lb/> the
                form sent and no other.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I regret you should have<lb/> taken no notice—not even by a line in
                reply—of<lb/> what I wrote you respecting the Occident. Three out<lb/> of the four
                subscribers to whom I <add>?</add> them have<lb/> viz, <persName>A Joseph</persName>
                &amp; <persName>M Benjamin</persName>
                <placeName>Quebec</placeName> &amp; <persName>Mrs Nooher</persName><lb/>
                <placeName>Toronto</placeName> have written me they receive them in duplicate<lb/> I
                have therefore ceased sending them to those places. From <persName>Messrs
                    Nordheimer</persName> I have not heard.<lb/> Your subscribers in
                    <placeName>Montreal</placeName> who now receive from<lb/> me are—<persName>Mr S.
                    Benjamin</persName>, <persName>J. A Joseph</persName>
                <persName>Miss S. Joseph</persName><lb/> etc <persName>Brabadi</persName>.
                    <persName>J. Ments</persName>
                <persName>J. Praddiau</persName> &amp;ct. <persName>D. S.</persName> = I<lb/>
                continue to send <persName>Piddiau's</persName> but he is a member of<lb/> the
                celebrated firm of which <persName>Dalphon</persName> is a partner<lb/> and I don't
                think he will pay—you had better</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>send 7 copies here, &amp; direct the <placeName>Quebec</placeName> &amp;
                    <placeName>Toronto</placeName><lb/> ones yourself. I sent out the extra nos I
                loaned<lb/> my own copy but could not succeed in getting<lb/> more subscribers
                thereby. The few who read have<lb/> the Messenger J. Chron &amp; Israelite, and
                although you<lb/> thought the change into a weekly demanded—nearly<lb/> all here
                would have preferred the monthly, because<lb/> “the could be more easily bound” an
                excellent reason.<lb/> The fact is <placeName>Canada</placeName> is but a poor
                market for Jewish<lb/> publications, even although <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                is comparatively<lb/> very superior to the cities of the <placeName>United
                    States</placeName>, for <hi rend="underline">every</hi> family<lb/> here has one
                paper. The English prefer the Jewish<lb/> Chronicle as a newspaper, the literary
                value of a<lb/> paper is not so much looked at. You have this<lb/> consolation—your
                circulate more than either of<lb/> the others. <persName>Isaacs</persName> without
                my permission used<lb/> to print my name as his agent, but when it<lb/> was pointed
                out to me I was obliged to request<lb/> him to withdraw it as although I will do
                what<lb/> I can to advance Jewish publications yet I cannot<lb/> have my name <hi
                    rend="underline">published</hi> as agent. There are always<lb/> those who think
                the line containing their name<lb/> the most interesting reading matter in the
                paper.<lb/> I handed him the name of <persName>E. Moss</persName>
                <add>?</add> in<lb/> a conversation with him I told him that<lb/> “the<add>?</add>
                were my sentiments.”</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Joseph</persName> has handed me a list of those<lb/> in
                arrears for the Occident, and having just returned<lb/> home, I will endeavor to
                collect what I can. A couple<lb/> of weeks since before a jaunt to the lakes I
                have<lb/> just taken—I addressed <persName>Mrs Naaher</persName> as in <persName>Mr
                    J's</persName><lb/> list she was down for three or four (I believe four)<lb/>
                years. <persName>Mr J.</persName> I know was most punctual in<lb/> giving her
                    <sic>numbe</sic> to young <persName>Solomon</persName> who <add>?</add>
                with<lb/> me to mail. I enclose <persName>Mrs J's</persName> ably-received<lb/>
                during my absence from home &amp; please let me know<lb/> what I am to do. You
                perceive she subscribes to<lb/> the Occident Advertiser. I regularly supply your<lb/>
                <placeName>Montreal</placeName> subscribers, and shall be very happy to<lb/>
                continue to do so if you prefer sending them this<lb/> way. I pay
                    <placeName>Canada</placeName> postage one cent on each<lb/> number.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have nothing of interest to write you hence.<lb/> I do not believe
                the Polish <sic>organation</sic> here will be<lb/> a strong one. It will not I
                believe interfere much<lb/> with us—for the next year not at all, as they<lb/> will
                continue to be members of our Congregation.<lb/> There is the usual <add>שנאה</add>
                between the Germans<lb/> and Poles. How do you get on—how your<lb/>
                <add>קהל</add>. I hope prosperously, and so believing<lb/> remain yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>Is my fathers paper on <persName>Reggioto</persName><lb/> finished—He inquired.</p>
        </body>
